information: Employers must contribute 3% of their employees' gross salary or wages to their KiwiSaver schemes and complying funds from their first full pay after 1 April 2013. This 3% is in addition to their gross salary or wages.

description: The value deducted from an individuals salary/wages.
information:
New or existing employees who are KiwiSaver members must contribute to KiwiSaver through their employer and have deductions made from their gross salary or wages, regardless of any other retirement scheme they may also be contributing to, unless they:
•Are on a valid KiwiSaver savings suspension
•Have reached the age of eligibility to withdraw and have completed a  KS51 Non-deduction notice

There is no minimum or maximum income thresholds for deductions (i.e. contributions apply to all gross salary or wages).

description: The Tax Credits Payroll Donation (TCPD) are the immediate benefit employees receive for making donations through their pay. The tax credit for payroll donations reduces the amount of PAYE for the employee.
information:
Tax credits for payroll donations are calculated using the formula: total donations x 33 1/3%

TCPD can not exceed an employee's total tax for that period.
Payroll giving donations can't be made from these income sources and types:
•Ministry of Social Development - Student allowances
•Ministry of Social Development - Benefits
•Ministry of Social Development - Pensions
•Accident Compensation - ACC payments
•Inland Revenue - Paid Parental Leave
•Withholding Tax (WT) payments

A new field to separately record deductions previously made under the ESS tax code
information:
Employers are now able to withhold PAYE, along with student loans and child support obligations on ESS benefits, by taxing them as an extra pay(lump sum). Employers will then include this information in the Employment Information (EI). 

Employers can choose not to withhold any tax however, in most cases they are still required to include the taxable value of the ESS benefit for each employee on the EI.

There are two instances where an employer is not required to show the value of the ESS benefit on an EI:
•The share benefit arises from an exempt ESS (formerly a "Commissioner approved" employee share purchase scheme). Refer to START Help: Exempt Employee Share Schemes.
•The benefits paid to former employees when they have elected not to make tax deductions.

If the employer chooses not to withhold tax on benefits an employee receives under an ESS, the obligation to pay tax on the value of the benefit remains with the employee. This will mean the employee may need to have an end of year square up and will either receive an Income Tax assessment or file an Income tax return.

This is an indicator on whether the charge was a family violence offence; with offences flagged as family violence in the Ministry of Justice Case Management System OR involving these specific offence types:
• assault on a family member (section 194A Crimes Act 1961)
• common assault (domestic) (section 9 Summary Offences Act 1981 or section 196 Crimes Act 1961)
• sexual offences against a spouse (section 128(4)/128B or section 129 Crimes Act 1961)
• incest (section 130 or section 131 Crimes Act 1961)
• coercion to marry (section 207A Crimes Act 1961)
• all offences included in the Domestic Violence Act 1995 (such as breach of protection order)
• all offences included the in the Family Violence Act 2018 (such as breach of protection order).

This indicator is only reliable for charges disposed from 1 July 2014.

information:
Allegation Audit – an allegation audit has resulted in a repayment to be made by the applicant

Default – initially used to show when a payment bounced back from an applicants bank account. When asked for a new account, they decided they no longer wanted to continue with their application. MSD now show these as Voluntary Disclosures.

Integrity Audit – an integrity audit (now called Integrity Check) that resulted in a repayment to be made by the applicant.

Investigation – an investigation has resulted in a repayment to be made by the applicant

Reconciliation – where the applicant may have paid the amount in full less 10c or 60c etc. If MSD doesn't “reconcile” the record, they will continue to show as a debtor. 

Voluntary Disclosure – the applicant let MSD know they need to repay some/all of the money they received as they no longer meet the criteria, e.g. they had included staff that had already left, were on ACC, or had died. Or they didn’t meet the 30% (or 40%) decline in income, or they applied twice under their personal and business IR numbers. Or they applied for the wrong subsidy.
